title: Buyers of underage sex are rarely prosecuted: 'We are at ground zero of the criminal justice response'
byline: By Lorraine de Foucher , Lucie Soullier and Thomas Saintourens
subhed: The French justice system estimates that 15,000 girls under the age of 18 are sexually exploited in France. The criminal response has focused on dismantling pimping networks, even though clients can also face criminal prosecution for the rape of minors when the victims are under 15 years old.

The last-minute fight to save Gaza's ancient archaeological treasures
subhed: Amid the vast destruction of the war, a small group of determined individuals fought to save Gaza's archaeological heritage. On September 10, they secured a few hours' reprieve from the Israeli army before a storage depot filled with artifacts was bombed to perform a delicate evacuation – the result of intense, high-level negotiations.

title: Andriy Yermak's resignation shocks Europe, but suits the US
byline: By Philippe Ricard, Piotr Smolar (Washington (United States) correspondent) and Philippe Jacqué (Brussels, Europe bureau)
subhed: With Volodymyr Zelensky's top aide stepping down, the EU loses a key interlocutor in Kyiv at a pivotal moment in peace talks. The Trump administration, by contrast, seems ready to leverage the crisis to push its own priorities.

title: 'Dédé la Sardine' and Russian oil: Inside the affair that has haunted Total for 15 years
subhed: Seven people have been ordered to stand trial for their involvement in an arbitration process that was allegedly manipulated in order to extract the equivalent of €16 billion from French oil company Total. Their trial begins on Monday.
